With so many great creators talking about AI agents helping with, well, everything, including running their newsletters, I finally decided to explore this space myself.

My first focus had to be content creation. I recently got a new job (yay\!), which leaves me with very limited time for Substack. And I‚Äôve been enjoying this journey too much to give up now. So here we are.

Besides, it‚Äôs an interesting problem to solve. If you‚Äôve ever tried to get an AI to replicate your writing style, you‚Äôll know this is harder than it sounds. The first few attempts were ... peculiar.

But I‚Äôm getting ahead of myself. Let‚Äôs start from the beginning.

#### **The ‚ÄúWHY‚Äù: Project Goals & Objectives**

To provide a little more personal context to this project, I recently started a new role as a Systems Consultant at an AI-powered data management start-up. This is my first proper ‚Äútech job", which I‚Äôm very excited about. And I get to work with AI and automations all day, learn new things constantly, and design cool, scalable systems.

But all the joy of getting a role in tech comes at a cost: my free time has gone down (a lot ü´†).

Before the new job, I was spending roughly 6-8 hours per Substack post. That included me writing the first draft, passing it to an AI chatbot like ChatGPT or Claude for proofreading and light editing, and then going back and forth a few times before the final version. And don‚Äôt even get me started on images ‚Ä¶

And now, by the time I finish work, cycle back home, prepare dinner, do all the mundane life admin, and spend some quality time with my husband, I‚Äôm left with maybe 30 minutes before I need to crash. Not exactly enough time for thoughtful content creation.

I faced a simple choice: either cut back on Substack (maybe to one post a month or stop entirely) or find a way to work smarter. And because I wasn‚Äôt going to give up that easily, I started thinking about how I could reverse my current writing process. Instead of writing the whole thing myself, could I get AI to produce the first draft for me to review?

**Here‚Äôs the goal for this project: create a system that can generate Substack and LinkedIn content in my brand voice with minimal edits.**

And more specifically, I was looking for:

* A system that could take my rough notes and turn them into a first draft that captures my Savvy Sloth voice.  
* Something I could review in 30-60 minutes, add my personal stories, jokes and tangents to, and hit publish on.  
* Zero budget (because I might be employed, but I‚Äôm still not a millionaire üò≠).  
* A first draft that was \~80% of the way to being publishable.

I also had a secondary goal of actually learning how to work with AI agents and build systems with them that would enhance my creative process and not substitute it.

#### **The ‚ÄúWHAT‚Äù: System Design & Overview**

Given that AI agents are now easy for almost anyone to use, the challenge of this project was not in the agents per se but more in the design of the system around those agents.

I very much value my audience and my Savvy Sloth brand, which I‚Äôve been working hard on, so I didn‚Äôt want a content generator that spat out generic AI slop. The whole point was to save time, not create more work rewriting drafts from scratch.

What I needed was a system that could read my rough notes and transform them into a post that sounds like me.

Here‚Äôs what the high-level flow looks like:

**Rough Notes ‚Üí Read & Understand ‚Üí Transform to Draft ‚Üí Format for Platforms ‚Üí Review & Publish**

Simple, right?\!

But if you‚Äôve ever used an AI chatbot to help you with writing, you‚Äôll know the struggle of 1\) making AI sound like you in the first place and 2\) AI having no recollection of what ‚Äúyou‚Äù sounds like the moment you start a new chat.

#### **The ‚ÄúHOW‚Äù: Ideal Tool Stack**

Here‚Äôs what I‚Äôve learnt from building automation systems: the more complex you make something, the more likely it is to break in ways you don‚Äôt expect.

So for the first iteration, I decided to stick with a basic MVP setup, if you like. I focused on a simpler question: what actually needs to happen for me to have a usable first draft?

The answer was surprisingly straightforward. I keep rough notes in various places (Notion, Apple Notes, sometimes just a text file when I‚Äôm being particularly disorganised). Those notes contain the core ideas, build logs, random links, and maybe a few half-formed thoughts.

What I needed was for someone (or something) to take my notes and transform them into a Substack article or a LinkedIn post that‚Äôs on-brand.

So the system needed to perform three core functions:

1. Reading and understanding my notes  
2. Transforming them into a structured draft  
3. Formatting for my specific platforms

For this project, I used the following tools:

**ü§ñ For AI Processing:**

* [**OpenCode**](https://opencode.ai/) (free **Big Pickle** model) as my automation environment  
* **Claude** as an AI agent setup assistant and brand voice generator

**üìù For Note-Taking:**

* **Notion** for structured notes  
* **Apple Notes** for quick captures  
* **Text files** for random thoughts  
* [**Wispr Flow**](https://wisprflow.ai/) for voice note capture

**üìÑ For Draft Management:**

* **Markdown files** for reference materials  
* **GitHub** for tracking changes

And here‚Äôs how these tools fit into our workflow:

![Flowchart showing content creation: rough notes in various formats coming from Notion, Apple Notes, text files and Wispr Flow pass through AI tools including Claude and OpenCode, ending with a Savvy Sloth logo showing a sloth using a laptop.][image2]

The cost breakdown looked pretty good on this system as well:

![Table listing tools with columns for Tool, Cost, and Purpose. Tools: OpenCode, Claude, Notion, Apple Notes, Text files, Wispr Flow. All are free.][image3]

As you can see, the minimal version of this workflow costs nothing to set up. That was important to me because I wanted to learn more about AI agents before investing in any paid tools, like Claude Code.

The Big Pickle model, which comes for free with OpenCode, was enough to test the approach. And once you have the system designed and core functionality working, upgrading the software would probably make more sense anyway.

#### **The Real Challenge: Capturing My Voice**

Now, the key frustration many people (myself included) have with AI writing is that it sounds like AI. It‚Äôs the kind of writing that‚Äôs technically proficient but has all the personality of a terms and conditions document.

Over the past few months, I developed a specific voice for Savvy Sloth. It‚Äôs transparent, sometimes self-deprecating, occasionally sarcastic, and I like to think it‚Äôs practical rather than theoretical. I don‚Äôt use em dashes, but I grossly overuse sloth emojis and parenthetical asides (like this one) to add side comments and random remarks. That‚Äôs what makes this Savvy Sloth, and not some other creator.

None of that comes naturally to an AI. It's trained on the internet, which means its output is 'averaged-out' writing. The exact opposite of my chaotic, conversational style.

So, I needed to teach AI. And that meant figuring out how to capture what actually makes my voice mine in a way that a machine would understand.

#### **The Initial Setup Checklist**

As usual, if you want to follow along with the build, I‚Äôm sharing quick initial setup steps so you can have everything ready for the next part:

‚úÖ **Set up your OpenCode account** (it‚Äôs free).

‚úÖ **Create a notes system.** I use a combination of Notion, Apple Notes, and text files, so pick whatever works for you.

‚úÖ **Gather writing samples.** Collect 5-10 posts that represent your voice well. These will be used to train the system on your style.

‚úÖ **Think about your content pillars.** You don‚Äôt need to have these nailed (we‚Äôll do that next week), but it‚Äôs good to get your creative ideas flowing.
